docs.abstract: Repurpose creamy risotto Milanese as a crispy, golden disc. No garnish needed.
docs.snippet: Repurpose creamy risotto Milanese as a crispy, golden disc. No garnish needed.
docs.lead_paragraph: Is it just a little over the top to ask you to make a fresh batch of risotto — 18 unbroken minutes at the stove stirring and stirring — just so you can have a pot of cold stuff the following day to make risotto al salto? Possibly. But to me, not any more over the top than the way I first had the dish at Antica Trattoria della Pesa, a sturdy and refined old restaurant in Milan that features traditional dishes of the Lombardy region of Italy. The risotto al salto came to the table on a trolley; there was heavy silverware, a woven cloth napkin on my lap. One perfect, saffron-gold disc on a bone white china plate. I don’t know if that’s excessive, even still. And yet.

headline.main: This Breathtakingly Crisp Risotto Cake Is Italian Perfection

docs.abstract: How a hedge fund’s efforts to take the island territory to the cleaners wound up before the Supreme Court — with ordinary Puerto Ricans arguing in the hedge fund’s favor.
docs.snippet: How a hedge fund’s efforts to take the island territory to the cleaners wound up before the Supreme Court — with ordinary Puerto Ricans arguing in the hedge fund’s favor.
docs.lead_paragraph: Puerto Rico filed for bankruptcy protection at 11:32 in the morning on May 3, 2017; by 11:33, the magnitude was obvious. No American territory had ever defaulted on so much debt. “A bankruptcy without precedent” ran a morning-after headline in the tabloid El Vocero, in an issue that also quoted leftist politicians warning readers not to be fooled: The filing, they claimed, was a prelude to more austerity. The island owed $72 billion. Already there was out-migration of 60,000 people a year and 10.5 percent unemployment. There were reports that vendors, owed millions of dollars, would no longer deliver food to Puerto Rican prisons.

docs.abstract: He became America’s most reliable comic star without ever leaving his comfort zone. So what’s he doing in this year’s most anxiety-inducing film?
docs.snippet: He became America’s most reliable comic star without ever leaving his comfort zone. So what’s he doing in this year’s most anxiety-inducing film?
docs.lead_paragraph: We cruised down West Pico in Adam Sandler’s ride, a custom Chevy passenger van tricked out in the style of an orthopedic shoe. The cup holders jangled with suburban odds and ends — a pair of tiny glasses belonging to his daughter; a bottle of Dry-n-Clear ear drops. We were bound for Hillcrest Country Club, the oldest Jewish country club in Los Angeles. “You’re going to like this,” Sandler said. He whipped the van into the valet station. Alongside the row of town cars and coupes, it looked like an airport courtesy shuttle.

docs.abstract: Include handles. Use cushioned seats. Make sure the upside person won’t be too earthbound.
docs.snippet: Include handles. Use cushioned seats. Make sure the upside person won’t be too earthbound.
docs.lead_paragraph: “Actions that take place on one side of a teeter totter have direct consequence on the other side,” says Ronald Rael, a professor of architecture at the University of California, Berkeley. For about 40 minutes on July 28, people on both sides of the United States-Mexico border, where New Mexico meets Ciudad Juárez, rode three bright pink teeter totters affixed to the towering steel border wall that were designed and installed by Rael and the architect and professor Virginia San Fratello. In planning your teeter totter, make sure that when one side is touching the ground, the other side will be twice as tall as the fulcrum in the middle. Don’t send the upside person dangerously high in the air, but don’t keep him or her overly earthbound either. “Part of the thrill is that your feet aren’t touching the ground,” San Fratello says.

headline.main: How to Build a Teeter Totter
